he kinds of safety and protection that are offered to (and withheld from) them. In so doing, he lays the framework for an original and compelling understanding of contemporary refugee subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGratitude. 0aRefuge in literature. 0aRefugeeszNorth America. 0aResentment. 0aResilience (Personality trait). 0aSoutheast AsianszNorth America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520397279zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520397279zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520397279/original  a978-3-11-079134-1 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA